<Link id="l00084" /><CodeLine lineNumber="84"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00085" /><CodeLine lineNumber="85"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// Handle the cases when we prefer one instruction over another. Case 1 - we</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00086" /><CodeLine lineNumber="86"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// prefer not to generate multiple loads in the packet to avoid a potential</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00087" /><CodeLine lineNumber="87"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// bank conflict. Case 2 - if a packet contains a dot cur instruction, then we</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00088" /><CodeLine lineNumber="88"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// prefer the instruction that can use the dot cur result. However, if the use</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00089" /><CodeLine lineNumber="89"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// is not scheduled in the same packet, then prefer other instructions in the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00090" /><CodeLine lineNumber="90"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// subsequent packet. Case 3 - we prefer a vector store that can be converted</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00091" /><CodeLine lineNumber="91"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// to a .new store. The packetizer will not generate the .new store if the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00092" /><CodeLine lineNumber="92"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// store doesn&#39;t have resources to fit in the packet (but the .new store may</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00093" /><CodeLine lineNumber="93"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// have resources). We attempt to schedule the store as soon as possible to</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00094" /><CodeLine lineNumber="94"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// help packetize the two instructions together.</span></CodeLine>
